<TEXT>
country people were just as poor during the 
economic recovery as they were during the last decades recession 
according to a study that found little difference between urban and 
rural poverty 
the study poverty in rural america a national overview said 
more than one in six people in rural america fell below the federal 
poverty line of 9056 for a family of three in 1987 while the rate 
was one in eight for residents of metropolitan areas during that 
year 
in fact the rural poverty rate for 1987 the fifth year of 
an economic recovery was as high as the rate for 1975 the 
deepest recession year of the 1970s said robert greenstein 
director of the center for budget and policy priorities while 
presenting the study tuesday to a hearing of the house select 
committee on children youth and families 
using data from the us census bureau on poverty from 1978 to 
1987 the center for budget and policy priorities found that the 
rural poverty rate rose from 135 percent to 169 percent 
in metropolitan areas during the same period the rate rose from 
104 percent to 125 percent metropolitan areas comprise one or 
more cities and their suburbs 
in the central cities which frequently are associated with 
poverty the rate climbed from 154 percent to 186 percent 
according to the study 
whats most striking is that the rate of poverty in rural 
areas is almost as high as in central cities greenstein said 
tuesday in an interview 
the center a nonprofit organization which conducts research and 
analysis on a range of public policy issues concerning lowincome 
families and individuals found the changes in poverty consistent 
among most racial ethnic age and demographic groups 
the rural poor are more likely to be white because there is a 
lower proportion of minorities in nonmetropolitan areas but more 
than twofifths 441 percent of nonmetro blacks were poor in 
1987 compared to onethird 333 percent of blacks living in 
central cities 
there also were more poor elderly people living in rural than 
urban areas the study said 
the only segment of the rural poor that was smaller than its 
urban counterpart was children according to the study 231 
percent of rural children were poor while 296 percent of the 
children in the central cities were poor in 1987 
but one feature that distinguished the rural poor from their 
urban counterparts is that rural poverty is likely to occur in 
twoparent families where one or both parents work 
nearly two of every three poor families living in rural areas 
contained at least one worker in 1987 the study said nearly 
one quarter had at least two workers 
</TEXT>
