first lady barbara bush underwent radioactive 
treatment today to destroy her thyroid gland because it is 
producing excess levels of hormones a condition that has irritated 
her eyes and caused her to lose 18 pounds in recent months 
shes just fine piece of cake never broke her stride mrs 
bushs press secretary anna perez said after the presidents wife 
returned to the white house following a twohour stay at walter 
reed army medical center 
the radiation was administered in an iodine solution sipped 
through a straw mrs bush said it was a colorless liquid that 
tasted like water ms perez reported 
doctors told mrs bush 63 that the only side effect she may 
suffer is a slight pain in the neck for several days she cracked 
jokes about that all day ms perez said 
moreover just as a precaution she shouldnt hug her puppies 
for a couple of days and she shouldnt kiss her grandchildren 
the spokeswoman said 
she explained that puppies and children have a heightened 
sensitivity to the radiation in mrs bushs body the first lady 
has 11 grandchildren and her dog millie recently produced six 
puppies 
mrs bush expressed surprise that her treatment attracted so 
much news media attention and was wondering why her visit to 
walter reed gets so much coverage when child help a nonprofit 
organization for youngsters doesnt her press secretary said 
a white house statement said the procedure has no significant 
side effects and has been a standard treatment for 40 years for 
people suffering with mrs bushs condition known as graves 
disease 
once her thyroid gland has stopped operating probably in two to 
three months mrs bush will have to take daily medication to 
maintain adequate hormone levels ms perez said 
president bush was asked about his wife at a white house 
ceremony for the college basketball champions while mrs bush was 
still at the hospital he replied fine when asked how she was 
doing 
mrs bush consulted doctors last month because of swelling and 
irritation in her eyes causing them to tear and the sudden weight 
loss 
for several weeks mrs bush has been treated with methimazole 
a drug that blocks production of excess hormones in the thyroid a 
butterflyshaped gland in the neck 
ms perez said the use of drugs was an interim therapy and that 
the destruction of the thyroid through radiation was a more 
permanent treatment 
left untreated graves disease can be lifethreatening but it 
generally responds quickly to therapy 
it is caused when antibodies attack the thyroid gland and cause 
it to secrete too much hormone 
the disease is more apt to occur in older women 
mrs bushs treatment with methimazole was discontinued sunday 
in preparation for todays procedure it will be restarted three 
days after the treatment and then continue until her level of 
thyroid hormones falls below normal 
mrs bush is under the care of white house physicians burton j 
lee iii and lawrence c mohr in consultation with dr kenneth 
burman a thyroid specialist at walter reed 
