<TEXT>
the united states has no compelling need for a 
commercially developed space platform proposed for use before a 
larger planned space station is put into orbit the national 
research council has concluded 
a report by the council released tuesday was based on a study 
by a panel of scientists and engineers 
its recommendations were counter to the proposal by the reagan 
administration for heavy federal support for the commercial space 
platform the national aeronautics and space administration had 
opposed the proposed venture as a possible competitor with its own 
space station to be put in orbit by 1996 
the report said there was no compelling need for a separate 
commercially developed facility for the conduct of research at low 
or zero gravity before then 
it said use of the space shuttle flights will accommodate the 
vast majority of anticipated experiments planned by nasa in the 
interim 
it said after the space station is built however construction 
of another facility for longterm microgravity experiments may 
well have merit if there are advances in microgravity research 
and space automation 
the report said the committee found no evidence to suggest 
that microgravity research would lead to significant spacebased 
manufacturing in the next five to 10 years 
the committee considers that microgravity science is at an 
immature stage due to lack of understanding of the fundamental 
processes involved in this area of space research the report 
said 
the reagan administrations 1988 space policy recommended 
support for an orbiting spacecraft for microgravity research which 
would be owned and operated by private business rather than nasa 
the federal government would be its main user however and would 
lease as much as 70 percent of the facility at a cost estimated at 
more than 700 million over five years 
the proposal for the private platform was developed by space 
industries inc of houston run by former nasa engineers and 
astronauts it said its space platform could be launched as early 
as 1992 
nasa requested the council study the scientific and commercial 
benefits of the proposal the council is an arm of the national 
academy of sciences 
