<TEXT>
a house subcommittee on wednesday approved a 
bill to reorganize the consumer product safety commission and 
require studies reports and decisions affecting a variety of 
products ranging from cigarette lighters to reclining chairs 
the bill was sent to the energy and commerce committee by the on 
commerce consumer protection and competitiveness subcommittee on a 
voice vote after rejecting an amendment that would have renewed the 
commissions basic laws without change 
congress has been unable to agree on such a renewal since 1983 
and the commission has operated under automatic yeartoyear 
renewals granted by appropriations bills last year the parent 
committee approved a bill almost identical to the one passed by the 
subcommittee wednesday but it was too late in the session for the 
house to act 
among major changes that would be made by the bill is the 
designation of two members as a quorum when there are only three 
members although the commission is authorized to have five 
members congress in recent years has appropriated money for only 
three salaries and a current vacancy means the commission cannot 
act at all because the quorum requirement is now three 
the bill would require among other things 
a study of flammability standards for pajamas and nightgowns 
used by the elderly 
a study of age requirements for operating amusement park rides 
a survey of reclining chairs for compliance with existing 
standards 
a report to congress on what the commission is doing about 
indoor air pollution 
the adoption of a standard for lighters to protect children 
the bill would also give state attorneys general the same power 
as the commission has to bring suits in federal courts and would 
permit consumers to petition for safety rules with a 120day 
deadline for action on such petitions 
the bill is backed by major consumer organizations but opposed 
by major business groups 
the author of the defeated amendment for a straightforward 
renewal rep howard c nielson rutah said i dont think 
there is any evidence the commission is not doing its job and i am 
particularly alarmed at the budget increase the bill would 
authorize 
the bill would set a ceiling on appropriations of 39 million 
next year and 40 million the year after nielsons amendment would 
have set ceilings of 34 million and 35 million the bush 
administration has recommended an appropriation of 335 million 
down from 345 million this year 
deaths caused by products under the commissions jurisdiction 
have fallen from about 26000 in 1975 to 22000 in 1984 and the 
per capita decline has been more dramatic because the population 
has grown nielson said 
i dont think its fair to the commission to put so many 
things in it the bill they cant handle he said 
