<TEXT>
after 20 days of arduous work and 
uncounted millions of dollars the worst effects of the nations 
biggest oil spill appear to be waning 
yet for all the work done by 1000 people on the water and 
shoreline and other thousands of support personnel much of the 
result is being attributed to the muscular forces of nature 
the natural processes have far outweighed ours jim hayden 
the states cleanup coordinator said earlier this week 
hayden and other officials acknowledge much of the easing 
situation must be credited to nature 
an estimated 30 to 40 percent of the 101 million gallons of 
oil that poured from the tanker exxon valdez has been dissipated by 
natural evaporation of the more volatile components of the crude 
oil by thursday less than 20000 barrels under 10 percent of the 
spill will have been recovered by human effort 
favorable weather through most of the 20 days since the spill 
pushed vast amounts of the oil out of prince william sound and into 
the gulf of alaska where several days of high wind and heavy seas 
churned and broke up the slick 
aerial observations this week indicated that some blackened 
beaches on the islands and inlets of the sound are being cleansed 
by the heavy wave action 
the spills disastrous effects are far from over it is feared 
the toll of wildlife will continue and even grow as migrating birds 
return to the oiled beaches 
it will be years before scientists know the impact on the vast 
ecosystem in prince william sound 
yet scientists are warning that nature must be given a big share 
of the cleanup work that remains they say too much human labor and 
technology applied to oiled areas could do more harm than good 
weve seen from other spills that if we hit an area too hard 
with things like high pressure water or heavy equipment we wind up 
killing everything said john robinson chief of the hazardous 
material response branch of the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration 
