<TEXT>
researchers at moscow university have achieved 
nuclear fusion at room temperature in tests similar to experiments 
carried out in the united states the official tass news agency 
said wednesday 
under the guidance of professor runar kuzmin researchers at 
the solid matter laboratory of the physics department of moscow 
university have confirmed the experiments of us colleagues to 
obtain nuclear fusion at room temperature tass said 
two weeks ago scientists at the university of utah and at the 
university of southhampton in britain said they had achieved fusion 
using ordinary laboratory equipment at room temperature 
their experiments used a rod of palladium and a coil of platinum 
immersed in a beaker of deuterium an isotope of hydrogen commonly 
found in seawater officials at the universities said 
however many experts reamined unconvinced that fusion actually 
took place in those experiments and some suggested the phenomenon 
may be something new to science 
tass indicated similarities between the experiments at moscow 
university and the campuses in britain and the united states 
kuzmin told tass that researchers inserted electrodes an anode 
and a cathode into a beaker of deuterium the electrodes were 
manufactured from titanium and palladium he said 
the researchers then applied electric current to the electrodes 
until the water reached a boiling point and registered the 
release of fast neutrons with the help of a detector the news 
agency said 
it is precisely judging by the release of neutrons that one 
can assert with confidence that the nuclear fusion reaction 
actually takes place kuzmin said 
he said the researchers made no attempt to calculate the ratio 
of energy applied to the energy released 
according to evaluations of us scientists this reaction 
probably releases four times more energy than is expended to 
stimulate nuclear fusion he said 
anatoly logunov a rector of moscow university told tass that a 
program of fundamental research into the new type of fusion will 
begin in the near future 
at this stage logunov said it is difficult to say whether 
the reaction would be economically profitable for obtaining energy 
on an industrial scale 
</TEXT>
