attorney general dick thornburgh on wednesday 
revoked a regulation promulgated by his predecessor that required 
the justice department to appoint independent counsels to 
investigate members of congress 
thornburgh who had previously expressed doubt about the order 
issued last summer as a parting shot by outgoing attorney general 
edwin meese iii rescinded the regulation after president bush 
proposed legislation to place lawmakers under the jurisdiction of 
the special prosecutor law 
thornburghs action returns to the justice department at least 
while congress studies the legislation its traditional role in 
investigating allegations of criminal wrongdoing by members of 
congress 
the congress has been asked to review the role of the 
independent counsel thornburgh said in a statement 
until that review is completed the previously established 
system for handling allegations of wrongdoing by members of 
congress which has worked well for many years will be followed 
the order was issued hours after bush proposed in his ethics 
package to extend to members of congress the law providing for 
court appointment of independent counsels to investigate high 
government officials 
the law currently applies only to highranking executive branch 
officials based on the presumption the justice department would 
have a conflictofinterest when called upon to investigate 
allegations against administration officials 
critics of the law which included former white house officials 
prosecuted under it contend it should also apply to members of 
congress 
meese himself the target of two independent counsel 
investigations that yielded no charges promulgated the regulation 
requiring that the attorney general appoint special prosecutors to 
investigate wrongdoing by member of congress 
thornburghs order means the public integrity section will have 
complete jurisdiction to investigate payroll padding allegations 
against walter fauntroy the nonvoting delegate from the district 
of columbia 
the justice department noted that since the public integrity 
section of the criminal division was established in 1976 20 
members of congress have been convicted of federal crimes 
the department is investigating allegations that fauntroy 
employed the son of rep gus savage dill on his house payroll 
while the younger savage was actually living in chicago 
it would also mean that pending any action by congress on 
bushs proposal the department would have jurisdiction to 
investigate any allegations of wrongdoing against house speaker jim 
wright dtexas 
justice department spokesman loye miller said the public 
integrity section is awaiting the results of the house ethics 
committee it will review the panels report to determine if a 
further investigation is warranted 
