the silent chase scene in woody allens bananas is another 
chaplininspired bit the filmmaker once said in an interview that 
he admired the way chaplin used thin plots on which to hang funny 
scenes 
chaplin could take the simplest human predicament and expand it 
into a lifetime a scene in the old tv series the 
honeymooners finds ralph and ed locked up in ralphs freezing 
apartment on a rent strike theyre running out of food and must 
eat celery for dinner ed art carney pretends the celery is a 
fullcourse steak dinner and eats with great flourish chaplin did 
a similar bit when he devoured his boot in the gold rush 
chaplin who died in 1977 following a stroke was born in 
lambeth a ghetto in the south of london the son of music hall 
performers his early years were difficult his parents charles 
and hannah were separated by 1892 his father rarely made child 
support payments forcing charlie and his older brother sydney to 
spend time in a local orphanage charlie was close to his mother 
but she was mentally unstable and drifted in and out of nursing 
homes 
i dont think he ever lost that thing about poverty 
recalled jerry epstein a longtime friend whose book remembering 
charlie has recently been released that haunts you one day 
you wake up and its all gone thats a living nightmare he once 
said to me what would have happened to me if i never left 
england 
chaplin showed talent as a mime and acrobat and first appeared 
on stage when he was 4 singing at a nearby music hall for a wildly 
appreciative audience of soldiers who threw money at the young 
performer by 1899 he had become one of the eight lancashire lads 
a traveling group of dancers and comedians 
in 1908 he became a comic with the celebrated fred karno 
company impressing and at times alienating peers with his 
singleminded devotion to his craft chaplin would later punctuate 
a creative dispute by insisting this is my work 
on a tour of the united states late in 1912 he was spotted by a 
talent agent the following year he signed a oneyear contract for 
150 a week with mack sennetts keystone films known for slapstick 
movies that concluded with spectacular chases 
chaplins first motion picture making a living was 
released in 1914 to generally favorable reviews although his 
character bore no resemblance to the tramp chaplin wearing a top 
hat monacle and droopy mustache portrayed a slicker who tries to 
scoop a reporter 
in his third picture mabels strange predictament he 
unveiled the tramp drawing on english music hall costumes he 
contrasted oversized pants and extra long shoes with a shrunken 
jacket and battered bowler hat adding a tiny mustache and walking 
cane to give the impression of a man aspiring for status but not 
succeeding 
he said the cane was the key to the whole characterization 
epstein recalled the minute he found that cane he knew he had 
the character he could attack people with it he could act like 
the gentleman with it 
chaplin gave the tramp a shuffling splayfooted walk that 
he picked up by imitating an old man called rummy banks who 
used to hold horses for coachmen outside a neighborhood pub 
audiences instantly responded a chicago reporter interviewed 
chaplin and commented you cant keep your eyes off his feet 
those big shoes are buttoned with 50 million eyes 
charlie chaplin cartoons began appearing in newspapers songs 
came out those charlie chaplin feet charlie chaplin the 
funniest of them all and the moon shines bright on charlie 
chaplin 
by 1916 chaplin was with the mutual film corporation making a 
staggering annual salary of 670000 and critics were starting to 
regard his films as more than just entertainment an article in 
harpers weekly the art of charles chaplin praised the star 
in ways comedians never were it compared the vulgarity of his 
films to the works of aristophanes and shakespeare 
in 1919 chaplin mary pickford douglas fairbanks and dw 
griffith formed united artists as a way of independently producing 
and financing their own films 
initially it was great said william everson a professor of 
cinema studies at new york university none of these people were 
getting the full results of their labor on paper it seemed ideal 
but financially it wasnt feasible 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

