<DOCNO> AP890412-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
chaplin began fleshing out his films mostly onereelers with 
social commentary relating the hardship faced by europeans coming 
to america in the immigrant and stressing the bonds shared by 
warring soldiers in shoulder arms 
his sentimental side emerged even more strongly in his feature 
films starting in 1921 with the kid which depicted the 
tramps friendship with an abandoned boy jackie coogan 
the film chaplins first fulllength feature grossed 2 
million made an instant star out of young coogan and gave full 
display to chaplins dramatic range his next feature the gold 
rush came out in 1925 and is regarded by chaplin and many 
others as his finest work 
inspired by stories of the 1898 gold rush the movie starred 
chaplin as the lone prospector and contained one of the most 
famous sequences in film history the dance of the rolls 
chaplin invites an attractive singer and her friends to dinner 
on new years eve and enthusiastically prepares the meal but his 
company never shows up and chaplin falls asleep he dreams about 
entertaining the guests by sticking forks in two dinner rolls and 
acting out a puppetlike dance on the table 
in another immortal segment hes stranded without food in a 
freezing cabin and boils his own boot consuming the dinner with 
considerable relish even twirling the laces like spaghetti 
chaplin often referred to an early love affair that would 
forever leave him with the desire to reach out for beauty a 
yearning he employed to heartbreaking effect in the gold rush 
and the circus in which the tramp falls in love with a circus 
girl 
in vain the tramp would pursue beautiful unreachable women 
never more movingly than in city lights in which he befriends 
a pretty blind flower girl and convinces her that he is a man of 
wealth and distinction 
as agee wrote the tramp is eventually brought down to painful 
reality when he raises the money necessary for the blind girl to 
regain her sight 
at the end of city lights she sees him for the first 
time she has imagined and anticipated him as princely to say the 
least and it had never seriously occurred to him that he is 
inadequate she recognizes who he must be by his shy confident 
shining joy as he comes silently toward her and he recognizes 
himself through the terrible changes in her face 
the camera just exchanges a few quiet closeups of the 
emotions which shift and intensify in each face it is enough to 
shrivel the heart to see and it is the greatest piece of acting 
and the highest moment in movies 
chaplins peers praised him in similar terms the great buster 
keaton repeatedly deferred to his rival as being in a class by 
himself writing that nobody ever made so many people laugh as 
did charlie with his little tramp 
although the onset of talking films in the late 20s ruined the 
careers of many stars notably john gilbert chaplin was reluctant 
to use sound complaining that dialogue to my way of thinking 
always slows action because action must wait upon words 
motion pictures need dialogue as much as beethoven symphonies 
need lyrics he once said 
city lights was chaplins last silent movie in 1936 he 
released modern times which had some crude sound effects and 
made a star out of paulette goddard the third of his four wives 
both movies were boxoffice hits as was 1940s the great 
dictator a stinging attack against hitler who bore an uncanny 
resemblance to the comic in 1941 his artistic dreams played 
second to his personal life he met and had a brief relationship 
with a young actress joan barry she later accused chaplin of 
fathering her child although blood tests backed up his claims that 
the baby wasnt his a california jury said he was causing 
considerable damage to his reputation and paving the way for 
rightwing branding of communism 
with mccarthyism in full and furious throttle chaplin an 
outspoken liberal and supporter of the wartime alliance with the 
soviet union came under harsh attack he had lived in california 
but had never become a us citizen considering himself a 
citizen of the world 
when he went to england in the early 50s to film limelight 
his entry permit was revoked the man who had embodied the american 
dream working his way from music hall performer to international 
celebrity lived his final years in vevey switzerland 
i never saw him depressed jerry epstein said he loved 
america he would say after all thats where i met oona 
oona oneill daughter of the playwright eugene oneill was 18 
when they married chaplin was 54 
she devoted her whole life to him epstein said she knew 
how to handle an artist oona is completely reserved 
selfeffacing never wanted the career never wanted the limelight 
she was in love with him her whole life 
she always said when i was young he looked after me now 
that hes an old man its my turn to look after him 
their eight children carved their own fame geraldine the 
oldest became an actress who soared to fame in david leans 1965 
epic dr zhivago josephine portrayed hemingways wife in a tv 
miniseries about the writer michael played one of the leads in 
king in new york when he was 9 all three children had walkons 
in limelight 
victoria runs a french circus called le cirque imaginaire 
eugene is a businessman jane lives in florida with ilya salkind 
producer of the superman movies annette recently appeared in a 
stage production of sam shepards buried child in france 
christopher 25 the youngest appeared in notes from the 
underground in london 
chaplin also had two children from his second wife lita grey 
sydney won a tony playing opposite judy holliday in bells are 
ringing and costarred with barbra streisand in funny girl 
on broadway charlie jr died about 20 years ago 
after monsieur verdoux flopped in 1947 chaplin never again 
regained his commercial appeal limelight released in 1952 
contained a memorable musical sequence with chaplin and buster 
keaton but had only moderate success he made just two more 
movies both poorly received a king in new york and a 
countess from hong kong a 1967 comedy starring marlon brando and 
sophia loren 
chaplin spent the last 10 years of his life collecting honors 
composing new scores for his movies and working on a project the 
freak it was never completed 
he returned briefly to the united states in 1972 to receive an 
honorary oscar from the academy of motion picture arts amp 
sciences the cannes film festival had paid tribute to him the year 
before and the venice film festival gave him a special golden lion 
award he received knighthood from queen elizabeth ii in march 1975 
a fan of the underdog to the end chaplin expressed admiration 
for sylvester stallones rocky murmuring excellent 
excellent as he watched the movie 
he just took life as it came epstein said he never spoke 
about death he never spoke about old age he felt he was still 
young he never lost his sense of curiosity 
</TEXT>
