<TEXT>
karen kocharian a darkhaired doeeyed boy who 
suffered a crushed hand when last decembers earthquake in armenia 
collapsed his school has spent the last two months in 
philadelphia undergoing reconstructive surgery as he awaits two 
more operations to give him operable fingers he absorbs american 
culture this is the third report in an intermittent series 
tracking karens progress the story is by associated press 
reporter bruce rule with laserphotos by photographer amy sancetta 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when karen kocharian arrived here two months 
ago for treatment of injuries suffered in decembers armenian 
earthquake he was a 9yearod in a gray suit who talked about 
soccer and chess now its blue jeans and sneakers video games and 
pee wee herman 
karen now 10 is one of 37 armenian children to be treated at 
10 american hospitals under a program sponsored by project hope 
four of the children including karen are being treated at 
childrens hospital of philadelphia 
karen lost his right eye and the fingers on his right hand when 
his grade school collapsed in the dec 7 quake which left 
thousands of his countrymen dead injured or homeless soviet 
doctors gave him a glass eye before he left for the united states 
although overwhelmed with curiosity when he first arrived he 
waited to ask questions until he was alone with annadid ohanian 
whose family is host to karen and karens father sarkis and he 
kept his bandaged maimed hand in his suit pocket 
finally fascination with that most american of love objects 
the automobile pulled karen out of his shell 
within days of arriving in february he had seen camaros 
porsches and cadillacs with a toy camera from the ohanians he 
shot two rolls of film photographing the ohanian family cars a 
corvette two fieros and a trans am from every angle 
when we go back he told his father firmly i dont want 
to ride in our afto mekana a nondescript russianmade car 
i will build my own car he said planning to work as an 
auto mechanic like his father 
his father sarkis also has changed 
at first quiet and reserved he is quicker to chat with 
americanarmenians who visit how do you do he says in english 
to other visitors 
sarkis a stocky 34yearold with specks of gray in his hair 
also has become more vocal about what he sees as shortcomings in 
the soviet system 
when the ohanians first brought sarkis to their small variety 
store in west philadelphia he was amazed at the number of 
available items 
he asked why cant we have this back home george ohanian 
said 
recently a tass reporter called from new york city 
sarkis answered questions with questions smiling and winking at 
the other armenians present 
who is going to pay for all this he was asked 
dont you know he replied adding not your country 
project hope will and my countrymen will 
later sarkis said he was angry because the soviets have placed 
severe restrictions on what he and karen can bring back to armenia 
project hope has been giving the childrens guardians 10 a day 
toward living expenses sarkis has spent most of the money on 
karen he has bought himself only a white jogging suit 
now he said he is afraid he will not be able to bring back any 
of the clothes or toys karen has received as presents since 
arriving here 
ohanian said the soviets have an official list of what may be 
brought into the country it specifies only one of each item one 
pair of pants one shirt one toy and so on 
sarkis has not yet told karen who continues to play with the 
matchbox cars and other toys hes received from wellwishers in 
places from northborough mass to tustin calif 
last month two of karens toes were transplanted to his right 
hand so he would have fingers the operation was not wholly 
successful and circulation problems developed so doctors sewed 
karens new fingers into a skin flap on his stomach to help with 
the healing 
the doctors say karen needs two more operations to build the 
toes into complete fingers 
naturally righthanded the boy takes therapy to strengthen his 
lefthanded abilities he plays magnetized pickup sticks bounces 
basketballs and writes letters for his physical therapist dore 
diberardino 
most days are spent at the ohanians store karen answers the 
telephone with a bright greeting armenian touch 
for lunch everyday he orders his favorite american sandwich 
corned beef on rye hold the cheese when he talks english words 
pop into his conversation 
at the ohanians suburban west chester home karen steers a 
riding mower around the backyard with his left hand wrenching the 
wheel back and forth 
recently he and his father were watching an armenianlanguage 
video baghdassar akhbar karen laughed occasionally at the 
family comedy but his eyes brightened when sarkis switched to 
pee wee hermans big adventure on cable television 
karen laughed at every visual gag hugging his stomach when pee 
wees motorcycle hit a billboard the boy screamed in english 
oh my god and fell back laughing 
for himself sarkis admits to enjoying sylvester stallones 
rambo and rocky movies 
they are much different now said ohanian an armenian 
immigrant who is housing the kocharians because he wanted to help 
the children who are armenians future 
they have come here to get medical treatment he said 
tousling karens hair but were sending them back american 
rebels 
