<TEXT>
wendys international inc is putting its 
money where its mouth is by offering customers a refund if they 
dont think theyve tasted the best hamburger in the business 
the promise is part of a sixweek advertising campaign in which 
wendys one of the nations largest fastfood chains proclaims 
itself the winner in a taste contest with industry leader 
mcdonalds corp the ad campaign started monday and ends in midmay 
charles w rath executive vice president of marketing said the 
suburban dublinbased company favors the tastetest over a campaign 
emphasizing discounts 
the problem i have with discounts is that if you lower the 
price then it must have only been worth that much in the first 
place rath said in an interview tuesday weve got a product 
that we have a lot of confidence in its worth and its value to the 
consumer nobodys done this before 
the moneyback guarantee is in addition to the companys policy 
of refunding money to dissatisfied customers under the special 
offer the company will refund the price of the hamburger to 
customers who do not agree that the one they just ate was the best 
in the burger business 
rath said the company did not estimate how much the special 
refunds would cost the company 
we dont think were going to lose any more than we would on a 
legitimate complaint of a product that doesnt meet our 
standards he said 
industry analyst malcolm knapp of the newyork based marketing 
research company malcolm knapp inc called the promotion a great 
proposition he said wendys came out no 1 in a taste test this 
year in restaurant and institutions magazine 
knapp said the strategy will cost the company less money than 
such promotions as couponing or discounts 
couponing always gives away products for sure and if you do 
discounting youre giving away money he said 
knapp also said the campaign will bring more people into wendys 
restaurants wendys is virtually tied for third with hardees food 
systems inc in size among national fastfood chains burger king 
a division of pillsbury co is second 
wendys spokesman denny lynch said the refund strategy was 
tested in eight markets last year it was never a problem he 
said 
he said customers trying to abuse the offer likely will be 
discovered because patrons tend to return to the same restaurant 
he also said only a few people would try to get refunds by going to 
several restaurants 
is it worth it to do that for 139 i dont think so lynch 
said 
the advertising campaign includes a claim of taste superiority 
over mcdonalds 
wendys contends customers surveyed at random in 1987 and 1988 
preferred wendys hamburgers by a 21 ratio over those offered by 
mcdonalds rath said the company hired cj research of chicago to 
conduct the surveys about 1500 consumers were interviewed 
quarterly 
mcdonalds spokesman john onoda was not available for comment 
tuesday and did not return a call seeking comment 
wendys with about 3750 restaurants nationwide has annual 
sales of nearly 3 billion it earned 285 million last year 
continuing to rebound from 1986 when it lost 49 million the 
company made 45 million in 1987 
