<TEXT>
a 750 million settlement in the washington 
public power supply system default case was the best deal that 
could be struck attorneys for a group of bondholders said 
that appraisal was made tuesday to us district judge william 
d browning at a hearing on how to distribute money from 
settlements reached late last year in the 225 billion wppss 
litigation 
representatives of a separate classaction suit for some 
bondholders argued that no settlement should be approved until 
browning decides individual bondholders and attorneys shares in 
the settlement 
they also said the state of washington should bear more 
responsibility for its role in the biggest municipal bond default 
in the united states 
after listening to about two dozen attorneys and other parties 
in the case browning said he would try to issue a written decision 
promptly 
defendants in the case which combined dozens of suits filed 
since february 1983 included wppss all 88 utilities that 
contracted with the consortium to build two reactors engineering 
firms wall street bond underwriters utility and wppss directors 
and blyth eastman an advisory firm 
in 1983 wppss defaulted on bonds it sold to finance 
construction of a nuclear power plant at the hanford nuclear 
reservation and another at satsop west of olympia 
the default was triggered by a washington state supreme court 
ruling that the participating utilities lacked the legal power to 
sign contracts with wppss guaranteeing payment even if no 
electricity was generated 
that ruling left bondholders no option but a fraud suit paul 
bernstein one of the attorneys for bondholders told browning 
melvyn weiss another plaintiffs attorney said any fraud case 
is difficult enough to prove to a jury let alone one with the 
dozens of contending parties 
weiss said he and other attorneys for bondholders felt the most 
they could achieve if they won the case was a 14 billion 
settlement 
the 750 million settlement was much more likely and it could 
well be much less he added 
bernstein estimated a settlement now rather than after years of 
litigation would add about 250 million to the value received 
al malanca attorney for the washington public utility group 
one of the defendants said he believed defendants stood an 
excellent chance of winning at trial 
he said that before the series of settlements were struck there 
was absolutely no movement toward agreement and these were the 
maximum dollars that could have been gotten out of anyone 
camden hall an attorney for seattle which at 50 million would 
pay the largest amount of any defendant also said he felt there 
had been an excellent chance of winning possibly through summary 
judgment 
hall said city officials wanted to settle to avoid millions of 
dollars in future legal expenses and escape the shadow cast by the 
wppss default over future bond issues 
seattle could afford to settle because the city had insurance 
unlike many defendants especially tiny public utility districts 
which had no money to pay for an adverse ruling 
bondholder arthur hoffer has led a classaction suit against the 
state on behalf of bondholders who believed the state would get off 
too cheaply the state agreed to add 10 million to the settlement 
in return for an end to liability 
richard lehman an adviser to the wppss bond investors 
association argued that nearly all of the 600 bondholders who 
responded to a questionnaire he sent were opposed to settlements 
with the state bonneville power administration and wppss and were 
willing to pursue court action to get a better deal 
browning told lehmann many bondholders referred to the 
questionnaire in their letters some apparently believing browning 
could do something to change the settlement so they would get the 
full face value 
it is not fair to leave that impression and let them think 
that the court system has somehow let them down the judge said 
bpa wasnt named in the original suit but agreed to pay 35 
million to get chemical bank the bondholders trustee and 
bondholders to abandon efforts to petition congress to allow a suit 
against the federal powermarketing agency 
wppss paid no money in its settlement in exchange for 
cooperation from its employees at the trial plaintiffs attorneys 
said there wasnt enough money left in wppss to pursue 
of five reactors being built by wppss in the late 1970s only 
one was completed 
