<TEXT>
northwest airlines has asked a federal judge 
to prevent los angeles billionaire marvin davis from meddling with 
its unions while davis who is seeking to buy the nations 
fourthlargest airline filed a separate lawsuit seeking to 
invalidate the companys poison pill takeover defense 
davis who has offered to buy northwests parent nwa inc for 
262 billion or 90 a share said the airlines litigation is 
without merit and infringes on workers rights to to satisfy 
themselves as to the plans and intentions of a new owner 
davis an oilman with interests in real estate and 
entertainment also said he planned a shareholder proxy fight to 
win control of the airlines board at the companys may 15 
shareholders meeting 
no hearing date was immediately set on davis suit filed 
tuesday in delaware court of chancery nwa is based eagan minn 
and incorporated in delaware 
meanwhile us district judge harry maclauglin in st paul set 
a hearing for thursday to consider northwests request for an 
injunction against davis to prevent him from negotiating with the 
carriers pilots and other union workers 
northwests suit also filed tuesday contended davis and his 
partnership were illegally interfering with the companies 
relations with northwest labor unions 
the suit claimed davis is trying to block completion of a 
collective bargaining agreement being negotiated between northwest 
and its 5000member pilots union 
the suit said davis contacted the air line pilots association on 
april 4 the day after he announced his takeover bid in a letter to 
the board of directors of nwa 
davis also has talked to the leader of the international 
association of machinists district lodge 143 which recently agreed 
to recommend adoption of a proposed new contract for 10500 
clerical workers at northwest the lawsuit said 
in addition davis had talked with the leader of the teamsters 
union which represents northwests 6500 flight attendents 
the northwest suit says davis and nwa co the partnership he 
controls are seeking to have the unions negotiate with them to 
usurp northwests contractual and statutory role and thereby to 
interfere with and disrupt northwests prospective and existing 
contractual and labor relations with its principal unions 
last friday nwas board of directors rejected davis offer 
calling it inadequate the board also reaffirmed its intention to 
maintain the nations fourthlargest airline as an independent 
entity 
kevin whalen a spokesman for northwest said tuesday the 
airline would not comment on davis suit at least until we study 
the complaint 
davis meanwhile called the northwest action entirely without 
merit 
northwests board approved the poison pill march 27 saying it 
wanted to make the company less attractive to a hostile suitor 
intending to break up the company 
the plan would take effect when a person or group acquires 15 
percent of nwas common stock or announces a tender offer that 
would result in ownership of 15 percent or more of the voting power 
of nwa stock 
the plan would allow the company to double the number of 
existing shares and offer them to shareholders other than the 
acquirer at half the market price said northwest spokesman bob 
gibbons 
the effect would be to require a hostile bidder to buy twice as 
many shares to gain control of the company making the bid twice as 
expensive 
davis complained in his suit that the plan would improperly 
interfere with the solicitation of proxies he expected to conduct 
in advance of the may 15 shareholders meeting 
he is seeking an order to temporarily restrain nwa from 
distributing special stockbuying rights to shareholders under the 
pill 
davis owns 3 percent of nwas stock shortly before he made his 
offer northwest announced that a separate group of investors was 
interested in buying nwa the identity of that group which owns 
49 percent of the stock has not been disclosed 
