<TEXT>
hewlettpackard co moved to seize 
leadership in the 4 billion computer workstation market wednesday 
announcing an agreement to buy apollo computer inc for 476 
million in cash 
hewlettpackards surprise announcement stole some thunder from 
rival sun microsystems inc which had chosen wednesday to announce 
what it called the most significant new products in its history 
apollo and hewlettpackard together would have 304 percent of 
the burgeoning workstation market capturing the lead from sun 
which has 283 percent according to dataquest inc a san 
josebased research firm 
the workstation market is expected to grow at a 30 percent clip 
through 1993 according to alea fairchild an analyst with 
dataquest 
workstations are singleuser computers that resemble personal 
computers but are usually quicker bigger and with larger screens 
and better graphics they were originally used mostly by scientists 
and engineers but are being increasingly targeted to everyday 
personal and business use 
it signals a real major commitment on our part to the 
workstation portion of our business said richard watts director 
of marketing in hewlettpackards computer products sector 
hewlettpackard will offer 1312 per share for apollos 
estimated 36 million shares of common stock outstanding and will 
begin its tender offer within five business days 
apollo shot up 462 to 1275 a gain of more than 50 percent 
in heavy overthecounter trading of 10 million shares 
hewlettpackard fell 75 cents to 5350 in consolidated new york 
stock exchange trading 
the deal requires regulatory approval and the tender of at least 
51 percent of apollo stock by shareholders 
apollo a fortune 500 company founded in 1980 and based in 
chelmsford mass was the pioneer of computer workstations but 
has suffered setbacks in the race with sun and lost money in two 
consecutive quarters last year it squeezed out a profit of 21 
million for the year as a whole on sales of 654 million 
apollo will likely operate as a division within 
hewlettpackards workstation group once the acquisition is 
completed which should be in 90 days said watts 
apollo chairman and ceo thomas a vanderslice termed the 
transaction a winwin situation for both companies he said he 
did not foresee major layoffs resulting from the purchase 
hewlettpackard said it will benefit from apollos strength in 
computer networking and its large customer base and motivated 
workforce 
hewlettpackard will bring its strength in the graphics area to 
apollo which could use the help as well as financial resources 
that includes 98 billion in revenues last year 
the hewlettapollo thing was pretty astonishing said 
michael murphy a senior analyst and editor of san franciscobased 
california technology stock letter what hewlett i think is doing 
here is building a lot of customer relationships that they are then 
going to migrate over into the unix world 
workstations run on unix an operating system that excels in 
communications and the ability to carry out multiple tasks 
simultaneously 
the announcement came as sun microsystems rolled out a line of 
sparcstation computers that boast sophisticated new graphics and 
digital sound plus higher speeds and a circuit board that allows 
fullmotion video on a computer screen it also launched a family 
of sun3 workstations 
i think that maybe is purely coincidental but it is 
interesting timing said barry f bosak an analyst with new 
yorkbased smith barney harris upham amp co 
i think it buys hewlett more visibility in an interesting 
market they certainly have the money to do it and apollo did need 
financial help said bosak who called the 476 million a fair 
price 
hewlettpackard had 169 percent of the 198788 market share and 
apollo had 135 percent dataquest said 
